] (Divorced)<br>Deborah Malumed\n|children        = 2\n|education       = [[Hobart and William Smith Colleges|Hobart College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Ohio State University]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]], [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])\n|website         = {{url|lowenthal.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''Alan Stuart Lowenthal''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|l|o\u028a|\u0259|n|\u02cc|\u03b8|\u0254\u02d0|l}} (born March 8, 1941) is an [[United States|American]] politician who has been the [[United States House of Representatives|United States Representative]] for [[California's 47th congressional district]] since 2013. A member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], he previously served in the [[California State Assembly]] from 1998 to 2004, representing the 54th Assembly district, and then as a member of the [[California State Senate]], representing the 27th district from 2004 to 2012. In both posts, he represented the city of [[Long Beach, California|Long Beach]] and its surrounding suburbs.\n\n==Early life, education, and academic career==\nLowenthal was born and raised in [[Queens, New York|Queens]], [[New York City]]. His family is Jewish. He graduated with a B.A. from [[Hobart and William Smith Colleges|Hobart College]] and earned a Ph.D. from [[Ohio State University]]. In 1969, Lowenthal moved to [[Long Beach, California|Long Beach]] and became a professor of [[community psychology]] at [[California State University, Long Beach]]. He went on leave to become a Long Beach City Councilman in 1992. He remained on leave for several years until retiring in 1998.<ref>http://lowenthal.house.gov/biography/biography.htm#.UifDnT-8G2k</ref>\n\n==California Assembly==\n\n===Elections===\nIn 1998, Lowenthal decided to run for the [[California's 54th State Assembly district|54th district]] of the [[California State Assembly]]. He defeated Republican nominee Julie Alban 50%-47%.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=280672</ref> In 2000, he won re-election to a second term defeating Republican nominee [[Rudy Svorinich]], a [[Los Angeles City Council]] member, 59%-39%.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=209624</ref> In 2002, he won re-election to a third term defeating Republican nominee Cesar Castellanos, 60%-40%.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=5705</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nIn the Assembly, Lowenthal authored [[Gun control in the United States|gun control in California]] that would ban gun selling in people's homes.<ref>http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LB&p_theme=lb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAE8C3DC10F421B&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM</ref> He was also a founding member of the Assembly's Bipartisan Caucus and authored legislation for the creation of California\u2019s first ever [[California Citizens Redistricting Commission|Bipartisan Citizens Redistricting Commission]].<ref>http://lowenthal.house.gov/biography/biography.htm#.UifDnT-8G2k</ref>\n\nSenator Lowenthal was named Legislator of the Year by the California Firefighters Association in 2002 after he passed a law that limited liability for organizations that donated firefighting equipment. The [[League of California Cities]] named him Legislator of the Year in 2001 due to his advocacy on behalf of local governments. He has also received the \"Rivie\" Award from the Friends of the Los Angeles River due to his efforts to help clean up the troubled river.\n\n==California Senate==\n\n===Elections===\nIn 2004, he decided to run for the [[California Senate]] in the [[California's 27th State Senate district|27th Senate district]]. He won the Democratic primary unopposed. In the general election, he defeated Republican nominee Cesar Navarro Castellanos 63%-37%.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=71765</ref> In 2008, he won re-election to a second term, defeating Allen Wood 67%-33%.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=331944</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nThe 47th District includes the [[Los Angeles County, California|Los Angeles County]] communities of [[Avalon, California|Avalon]], [[Long Beach, California|Long Beach]], Signal Hill, [[Lakewood, California|Lakewood]], [[Cerritos, California|Cerritos]], [[Artesia, California|Artesia]], [[Bellflower, California|Bellflower]], [[Downey, California|Downey]], [[South Gate, California|South Gate]], [[Lynwood, California|Lynwood]], [[Paramount, California|Paramount]], [[Hawaiian Gardens, California|Hawaiian Gardens]], Florence-Graham and [[Willowbrook, California|Willowbrook]].\n\nOther legislation that Senator Lowenthal has had signed into law include a law to reduce diesel emissions at the ports by limiting idling time for trucks conducting transactions at the ports, a bill that established a grant program to provide financial incentives for purchasing or leasing electric vehicles, and a bill to protect highways.\n\nWith Bonnie Lowenthal's election to the Assembly and Alan Lowenthal's reelection in 2008, Senator and Assemblywoman Lowenthal were the first divorced husband and wife to serve concurrently in the [[California State Legislature]].\n\nLowenthal provided significant commentary throughout the documentary ''[[Who Killed the Electric Car?]]''.\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*Senate Committee Education (Chair) \n*Select Committee on California Ports and Goods Movement<ref>{{cite news|title=Planning Report|url=http://www.planningreport.com/2005/03/30/state-sen-lowenthal-presses-balanced-environment-economic-agenda}}</ref>\n*Select Committee on High-Speed Rail (Chair)<ref>{{cite news|title=Contra Costa Times|url=http://www.contracostatimes.com/ci_19737244}}</ref>\n*Senate Environmental Quality Committee<ref>{{cite news|title=Planning Report|url=http://www.planningreport.com/2005/03/30/state-sen-lowenthal-presses-balanced-environment-economic-agenda}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===2012 election===\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in California, 2012#District 47}}\nOn November 6, 2012, Lowenthal was elected to the [[U.S. House of Representatives]] from the newly created [[California's 47th congressional district|47th District]] after defeating Republican [[Gary DeLong (politician)|Gary DeLong]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Saltzgaver|first=Harry|title=Lowenthal To Represent Long Beach In Congress|url=http://www.gazettes.com/news/government/lowenthal-to-represent-long-beach-in-congress/article_00f73b1c-2930-11e2-ad37-0019bb2963f4.html|work=gazettes.com|accessdate=7 November 2012}}</ref> Although DeLong carried the [[Orange County, California|Orange County]] portion of the district with 54 percent of the vote, Lowenthal swamped him in the [[Los Angeles County]] portion by over 38,000 votes, more than the actual margin of 30,100 votes.  He took office on January 3, 2013.  He is the first non-Hispanic Democrat to represent a significant portion of traditionally heavily Republican Orange County in Congress since [[Jerry M. Patterson]], who served from 1975 to 1985.  In much of the Orange County portion of the district, he is the only elected white Democrat above the county level.  However, the Los Angeles County portion has more than double the population of the Orange County portion.\n\nLowenthal was reelected in 2014 by a similar margin.\n\nHe is a member of the [[Congressional Progressive Caucus]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://cpc.grijalva.house.gov/index.cfm?sectionid=71&sectiontree=2,71|format=|publisher=Congressional Progressive Caucus|date=|accessdate=12 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022024104/https://cpc.grijalva.house.gov/index.cfm?sectionid=71&sectiontree=2,71|archive-date=2017-10-22|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure]]'''\n**[http://democrats.transportation.house.gov/subcommittees/highways-and-transit-114th-congress Subcommittee on Highways and Transit]\n**[http://democrats.transportation.house.gov/subcommittees/water-resources-and-environment-114th-congress Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment]\n**[http://democrats.transportation.house.gov/subcommittees/coast-guard-and-maritime-transportation-114th-congress Subcommittee on Coast Guard and Maritime Transportation]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Natural Resources|Committee on Natural Resources]]'''\n**[[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on Energy and Mineral Resources|Subcommittee on Energy and Mineral Resources]]\n**[[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on Fisheries, Wildlife, Oceans and Insular Affairs|Subcommittee on Fisheries, Wildlife, Oceans and Insular Affairs]]\n**[[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on Water and Power|Subcommittee on Water and Power]]\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* [[House Baltic Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=http://housebalticcaucus.webs.com/members|format=|publisher=House Baltic Caucus|date=|accessdate=21 February 2018}}</ref>\n*'''[[Congressional Arts Caucus]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Membership|author=|url=https://artscaucus-slaughter.house.gov/membership|format=|publisher=Congressional Arts Caucus|date=|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref>\n*[[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Members|author=|url=https://royce.house.gov/internationalconservation/members.html|format=|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives International Conservation Caucus |date=|accessdate=2 August 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Climate Solutions Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=90 Current Climate Solutions Caucus Members|author=|url=https://citizensclimatelobby.org/climate-solutions-caucus/|format=| publisher=Citizen\u00b4s Climate Lobby |date=|accessdate=18 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe is married to Deborah Malumed, MD. His son Daniel is an elected judge to the Los Angeles County Superior Court.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Jewish members of the United States Congress]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://lowenthal.house.gov/ Congressman Alan Lowenthal] official U.S. House website\n*[http://www.alanlowenthal.com/ Alan Lowenthal for Congress]\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/California/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Alan_Lowenthal_%5BD-47%5D}}\n* {{C-SPAN|alanlowenthal}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=L000579 | votesmart=16469 | fec=C00498212 | congress=alan-lowenthal/L000579 }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-ca-hs}}\n{{succession box |title=[[California State Assembly]]member<br />[[California's 54th State Assembly district|54th District]] |before=[[Steven T. Kuykendall]] |after=[[Betty Karnette]] |years=December 7, 1998\u2013November 30, 2004}}\n{{s-par|us-ca-sen}}\n{{succession box |title=[[California State Senate|California State Senator]]<br />[[California's 27th State Senate district|27th District]]|before=[[Betty Karnette]] |after=[[Fran Pavley]] |years=December 6, 2004\u2013December 3, 2012}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox\n| state=California\n| district=47\n| before=[[Loretta Sanchez]]\n| start=January 3, 2013\n}}\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Doug LaMalfa]]<br>R-[[California]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=''[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]''|years=276th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Michelle Lujan Grisham]]<br>D-[[New Mexico]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{CA-FedRep}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lowenthal, Alan}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:California city council members]]\n[[Category:California Democrats]]\n[[Category:California state senators]]\n[[Category:California State University, Long Beach faculty]]\n[[Category:Hobart and William Smith Colleges alumni]]\n[[Category:Jewish members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Li